<div id="review_2625274154" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2625274154" />
    <a title="Linda" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35179119-linda"><img alt="Linda" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472492541p2/35179119.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2625274154?book_show_action=true">Nov 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda" href="/user/show/35179119-linda">Linda</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35179119-linda?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35179119-linda?shelf=american-fiction">american-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2625274154" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2589562844232689541">It is refreshing to read about a decent man with a sense of integrity in these troubled times. John Ames, the protagonist of Gilead, is such a man. He is a third-generation Congregationalist minister from Kansas. His first wife and child died in childbirth, and Ames spent most of his adult life as a lonely man dedicated to his congregation, community, and faith. At 67, he met and married Lila, a much younger woman, and they had a son. When his son turned seven, Ames learned that he had little ti</span>
  <span id="freeText2589562844232689541" style="display:none">It is refreshing to read about a decent man with a sense of integrity in these troubled times. John Ames, the protagonist of Gilead, is such a man. He is a third-generation Congregationalist minister from Kansas. His first wife and child died in childbirth, and Ames spent most of his adult life as a lonely man dedicated to his congregation, community, and faith. At 67, he met and married Lila, a much younger woman, and they had a son. When his son turned seven, Ames learned that he had little time left to live and decided to write a letter to his son so that as an adult, he can know something of his father and his father's family. <br /><br />Robinson set this finely crafted epistolary novel in 1956, yet it spans three generations and examines the father/ son relationship. There are vivid and often humorous stories of Ames' grandfather, a fiery abolitionist who rode with John Brown and lost an eye in the Civil War. He also shares tales about his pacifist father and agnostic brother, an adherent of Feuerbach. While there is much discussion of religious ideas, Ames finds it hardest to put his beliefs into practice in his relationship with his godson and namesake, a non- believer, who in his youth had behaved in a way that Ames found morally reprehensible. The resolution of this inner conflict is central to this Pulitzer Prize-winning novel. Regardless of one's religious affiliation or lack thereof, this finely crafted character study is well worth reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2589562844232689541" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

